Furui translates prāk-pravr̥ttā maryyādā (l14) as "custom practiced in the east" - I'm pretty certain it should be translated "old-established custom".
--><!--
For vāpakṣetra in l14-15, see my note on l11 of the Faridpur charter of Dharmāditya, year 3 (IN00128). I am still uncertain about the interpretation, but still inclined to believe that tathā is used in the sense of "and". Furui transcribes tathā-vāpa and translates. "Such vāpas of (i.e. size of) land plots are sold..."
--><!--
As for akr̥ta-kalanā etc (l15), he translates "with only observation without calculation made." This makes good sense except for the gender agreement problem; it's certainly better than khaṇḍala-kr̥ta etc in l11 of IN00128. We'd need to emend to khaṇḍā akr̥ta [as suggested by Griffiths to Furui].
--><!--
In l16 Furui reads kr̥tābhilāṣyaḥ (and emends as adopted here; compare IN00128:14). Given that s and ṣ are basically indistinguishable, I think °ābhilāsyaḥ is a more likely error in place of kr̥tābhilāṣasya.
--><!--
In l17 I adopt Furui's reading of sāṅkalpā°, but perhaps the original is rather saṁṅkalpā.
--><!--
I'm not sure about krīyatām in l17; I follow Furui but note that only an (apparently short) i mātrā is clear; krī is very plausible, but kri would also be possible.
--><!--
In l17 Furui emends dīnārāsr̥dya to dīnārām āsr̥jya (sic, the intent must be dīnārān). I have no better idea.
--><!--
Furui notes that the first 6 characters of l18 may have been erased and overwritten. I see no indication of this, but the characters are much damaged here, and not only the first 6. I provisionally adopt Furui's reading; mine would be s(u)dha(n)a-(śrī)-#1#(?ya)laga(?r)(tt)(?e) (yathā-pradhānād)i-kuṭumvino. Of this, yathā-pradhānādi seems better than sapradhānādi, and it also gives us a locative (Furui finds one in "Pasadhanakagdhaṅga").
--><!--
For °bhivyañcitaka in l18, Furui suggets the emendation °bhivyañjitaka, translating "(divided it) by manifested procedure", whatever that may mean. I recognise nothing of these two characters in the photo and find the reading very dubious.
--><!--
There may be another character between krameṇa and tad in l18; it's probably e if it's anything.
--><!--
In l19 Furui reads -kr̥taṁ vibhāgam, taking vibhāgam as the subject of the sentence, "a part (of land) with four borders fixed". I do not see the anusvāra and find this interpretation tenuous; catus-sīmā-kr̥ta-vibhāgam seems to make better sense. Admittedly, we then don't have a subject, which was either omitted or meant to be understood; we'd expect kṣettra-kulya-vāpa-dvayam on analogy with similar plates.
--><!--
At the very end of l19 Furui reads an unclear thā (giving vibhāgam athāsmābhir). I see only a smudge after ma, and find the sentence better without an atha. (Although the nte of śrūyante at the end of l27 is just as faint and just as much out on the fringe.)
--><!--
In this list again I follow Furui in putting spaces after proper case endings and hyphens after stem forms - but obviously we again have a loosely grammatical structure in which words are meant more like nominatives, though they are suffixed with ādi. (Cf. the varying ending mi/mī.) Also, I believe svāmino in l23 should be emended to svāminau: we wouldn't expect a genitive here, but a dual nominative makes sense.
--><!--
Furui interprets deyaka and candrikā as toponyms, which would be surprising since no such places have been mentioned. I'm more inclined to understand deyaka as "the thing which is to be donated", though I have no idea about candrikā. Furui counts the quarters on p96, and comes to three quarters in total (two quarters and two half-quarters), proposing that the final quarter is to be shared by the last 7 (or more) brāhmaṇas - which makes sense, and which also shows that these are quarters and half-quarters of the plot, not of separate villages.
--></p>
